{"title_page": "Amateur radio propagation beacon", "text_new": "{{broader|Electric beacon}}\nAn '''amateur radio propagation beacon''' is a [[radio beacon]], whose purpose is the investigation of the [[radio propagation|propagation]] of radio signals. Most radio propagation beacons use [[amateur radio]] frequencies.  They can be found on [[Low frequency|LF]], [[Medium frequency|MF]], [[High frequency|HF]], [[Very high frequency|VHF]], [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]], and [[microwave]] frequencies.   Microwave beacons are also used as signal sources to test and calibrate antennas and receivers.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Andy Talbot, G4JNT| title=Amateur Beacons | journal=Radio User| issn=1748-8117 |date=May 2008 | volume=3 | issue=5 | pages=56\u201358 }} The article includes the following definition for beacons licensed in the Amateur Radio service: \"A station in the Amateur Service or Amateur Satellite Service that autonomously transmits in a fixed format, which may include repeated data or information, for the study of propagation, determination of frequency or bearing, or for other experimental purposes\".</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first1=Andy (G4JNT) |last1=Talbot |title=Amateur Beacons |journal=Radio User |issn=1748-8117 |date=August 2008 |volume=3 |issue=8 |pages=30\u201333 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Amateur Radio Union]] (IARU) and its member societies coordinate beacons established by radio amateurs.\n[[File:4U1UN beacon.ogg|thumb|right|Propagation beacon 4U1UN, transmitting from the [[headquarters of the United Nations]] in New York]]\n\n==Transmission characteristics==\nMost beacons operate in [[continuous wave]] (A1A) and transmit their identification ([[call sign]] and location). Some of them send long dashes to facilitate signal strength measurement. A small number of beacons transmit [[Morse code]] by [[frequency shift keying]] (F1A). A few beacons transmit signals in digital modulation modes, like [[radioteletype]] (F1B) and [[PSK31]] (G1B).\n\n==Legality==\nIn the US, unattended beacons on frequencies lower than the 10-meter band are not legal.<ref name=\"Keeton\">{{cite web |url=https://groups.io/g/QRPLabs/message/12013 |title=Re: Beacon Operating frequencies |first1=Kelly R. (K7MHI) |last1=Keeton |date=17 November 2016 |accessdate=28 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==2200-meter beacons==\nAmateur experiments in the [[2200-meter band]] (135.7\u2013137.8&nbsp;kHz) often involve operating temporary beacons.\n\n==1750-meter beacons==\nIn the United States and Canada, unlicensed experimenters (\"[[LowFER]]s\") establish low power beacons on radio frequencies between 160&nbsp;kHz and 190&nbsp;kHz.\n\n==160-meter beacons==\nThe International Amateur Radio Union [[International Telecommunication Union region|Region 2]] ([[North America|North]] and [[South America]]) bandplan for the [[160-meter band]] reserves the range 1999&nbsp;[[kilohertz|kHz]] to 2000&nbsp;kHz for propagation beacons.\n\n==10-meter beacons==\nMost [[high frequency]] radio propagation beacons are found in the [[10-meter band]] (28&nbsp;MHz), where they are good indicators of [[Sporadic E]] ionospheric propagation.  According to IARU bandplans, the following 28&nbsp;MHz frequencies are allocated to radio propagation beacons:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! IARU Region\n! Beacon Sub-bands (MHz)\n|-\n| R1\n|\n* 28.190\u201328.199 Regional time-shared\n* 28.199\u201328.201 The International Beacon Project\n* 28.201\u201328.225 Continuous duty\n|-\n| R2<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/>\n|\n* 28.190\u201328.199 Regional time-shared\n* 28.199\u201328.201 The International Beacon Project\n* 28.201\u201328.225 Beacons, continuous duty\n* 28.225\u201328.300 Shared\n|-\n| R3\n|\n* 28.190\u201328.200 The International Beacon Project\n|}\n\n==6-meter beacons==\nDue to unpredictable and intermittent long distance propagation, usually achieved by a combination of ionospheric conditions, beacons are very important in providing early warning for [[6-meter band]] (50&nbsp;MHz) openings. Beacons operate in the lower part of the band, traditionally in the range 50.000&nbsp;MHz to 50.080&nbsp;MHz.\n\nThe IARU is encouraging individual beacons to move to 50.4&nbsp;MHz to 50.5&nbsp;MHz to assist with the establishment of the [[#Synchronized Beacon Project|Synchronized Beacon Project]].<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>  In the [[United States]], the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) only permits unattended 6-meter beacon stations to operate between 50.060&nbsp;and 50.080&nbsp;MHz.<ref name=\"T47CFR97.203d\">{{CodeFedReg|47|97|203|(d)}}</ref>\n\n==4-meter beacons==\nSeveral countries in [[International Telecommunication Union region|ITU Region 1]] have access to frequencies in the 70&nbsp;MHz region, called the [[4-meter band]].  The band shares many propagation characteristics with 6 meters.  The preferred location for beacons is 70.000\u201370.090&nbsp;MHz;<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/> however, in countries where this segment is not allocated to Amateur Radio, beacons may operate elsewhere in the band.\n\n==VHF/UHF beacons==\nBeacons on 144&nbsp;MHz and higher frequencies are mainly used to identify [[Radio propagation#Tropospheric modes|tropospheric radio propagation]] openings. It is not uncommon for VHF and UHF beacons to use directional antennas.  Frequencies set aside for beacons on VHF and UHF bands vary widely in different ITU regions and countries.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Band\n! colspan=\"3\" | Beacon Sub-band (MHz)\n|-\n! ITU Region 1\n! ITU Region 2\n! ITU Region 3\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2 meters|2&nbsp;m]]\n| align=\"center\" | 144.400\u2013144.491<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 144.275\u2013144.300<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | none<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[1.25 meters|1.25&nbsp;m]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| align=\"center\" | 222.050\u2013222.060<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[70 centimeters|70&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 432.400\u2013432.490<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 432.300\u2013432.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | none<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[33 centimeters|33&nbsp;cm]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| align=\"center\" | 903.000\u2013903.100<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[23 centimeters|23&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 1,296.800\u20131,296.994<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 1,296.200\u20131,296.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | none<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[13 centimeters|13&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 2,320.800\u20132,321.000<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 2,304.300\u20132,304.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 2,304.300\u20132,304.400<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\nThe beacon sub-bands in the [[United Kingdom]] also reflect IARU Region 1 recommendations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qsl.net/g3yrc/Bandplans/UK%20VHF.htm |title=Amateur Radio UK VHF Bandplan |accessdate=2008-04-27 |website=Great Yarmouth Radio Club |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531002059/http://www.qsl.net/g3yrc/Bandplans/UK%20VHF.htm |archive-date=2008-05-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==SHF/microwave beacons==\nIn addition to identifying propagation, microwave beacons are also used as signal sources to test and calibrate antennas and receivers.  [[Super high frequency|SHF]] beacons are not as common as beacons on the lower bands, and beacons above the [[3-centimeter band]] (10&nbsp;GHz) are unusual.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Band\n! colspan=\"3\" | Beacon Sub-band (MHz)\n|-\n! ITU Region 1\n! ITU Region 2\n! ITU Region 3\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[9 centimeters|9&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 3,400.800\u20133,400.995<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 3,456.300\u20133,457.000<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 3,456.300\u20133,457.000<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[5 centimeters|5&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5,760.800\u20135,760.990<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 5,760.300\u20135,761.000<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 5,760.300\u20135,761.000<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[3 centimeters|3&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 10,368.800\u201310,368.990<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 10,368.300\u201310,368.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 10.368.300\u201310.368.400<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[1.2 centimeters|1.2&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 24,048.800\u201324,048.995<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 24,048.750\u201324,048.995<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 24,048.750\u201324,048.995<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|}\n\n==Beacon projects==\nMost radio propagation beacons are operated by individual radio amateurs or amateur radio societies and clubs. As a result, there are frequent additions and deletions to the lists of beacons. There are, however a few major projects coordinated by organizations like the [[International Amateur Radio Union]] (IARU).\n\n===IARU Beacon Project===\n{{main|International Beacon Project}}\n[[File:NCDXF beacons.ogg|thumb|right|Beacons from Finland and Madeira on 14.100&nbsp;MHz]]\nThe International Beacon Project (IBP), which is coordinated by the [http://www.ncdxf.org/pages/beacons.html Northern California DX Foundation] and the [[International Amateur Radio Union]], consists of 18&nbsp;[[high frequency]] propagation beacons worldwide, which transmit in turns on 14.100&nbsp;MHz, 18.110&nbsp;MHz, 21.150&nbsp;MHz, 24.930&nbsp;MHz, and 28.200&nbsp;MHz.<ref name=\"ncdxf\">{{cite web\n |publisher=Northern California DX Foundation \n |year=2008 \n |url=http://www.ncdxf.org/beacons.html \n |title=International Beacon Project \n |accessdate=2008-02-27 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227235431/http://www.ncdxf.org/beacons.html \n |archivedate=2007-12-27 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n===DARC Beacon Project===\nThe [[Deutscher Amateur-Radio-Club]] sponsors two beacons which transmit from [[Scheggerott]], near [[Kiel]] ({{Coor Maidenhead|54.6875|9.79167|yes}}).<ref>{{cite web |title=Aurora beacon DK\u00d8WCY |url=http://www.dk0wcy.de |website=[[Deutscher Amateur-Radio-Club]] e.V. (DARC) |accessdate=2008-05-03 |year=2004 }}</ref> These beacons are DRA5 on 5195&nbsp;kHz and DK0WCY on 10144&nbsp;kHz. In addition to identification and location, every 10 minutes, these beacons transmit solar and [[geomagnetic]] bulletins. Transmissions are in Morse code for aural reception, RTTY and PSK31.<ref>{{cite book | title=Technical Topics Scrapbook{{Snd}} All 50 years | chapter=The DK0WCY/DRA5 Propagation Beacons | pages=98 | author=Pat Hawker, G3VA | publisher=[[Radio Society of Great Britain]] | year=2008 | isbn=978-1-905086-39-9 | location=Potters Bar, UK }}</ref> DK0WCY operates also a limited service beacon on 3579&nbsp;kHz at 0720\u20130900 and 1600\u20131900 local time.\n\n===RSGB 5 MHz Beacon Project===\nThe [[Radio Society of Great Britain]] operates a radio propagation beacon GB3ORK on 5290&nbsp;kHz, transmitting every 15 minutes commencing at 2 minutes past the hour.  It is located in the [[Orkney Islands]] ({{Coor Maidenhead|59.0208|-3.20833|yes}}).\n\n===The GB3RAL VHF Beacon Cluster===\nGB3RAL, which is located at the [[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]], transmits continuously on a number of low-band and mid-band VHF frequencies{{Snd}} 40050, 50050, 60050 and 70050&nbsp;kHz{{Snd}} as well as 28215&nbsp;kHz in the 10-meter amateur band.<ref>{{cite journal\n| journal=RadCom\n| publisher=[[Radio Society of Great Britain]]\n| pages=65\u201369\n| title=The GB3RAL VHF Beacon cluster\n| author=Mike Willis, G0MJW\n| volume=84\n| issue=4\n| issn=1367-1499\n| date=April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Weak Signal Propagation Reporter Network (WSPR)===\nA large-scale beacon project is underway using the WSPR transmission scheme included with the [[WSJT (Amateur radio software)|WSJT]] software suite.  The loosely coordinated beacon transmitters and receivers, collectively known as the WSPRnet, report the real-time propagation characteristics of a number of frequency bands and geographical locations via  \nthe Internet.  The WSPRnet website provides detailed propagation report databases and real-time graphical maps of propagation paths.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcome to the Weak Signal Propagation Reporter Network |url=http://wsprnet.org |website=[[WSPR (amateur radio software)|WSPRNet]] }}</ref>\n\n===Synchronized Beacon Project===\nThe Synchronized Beacon Project (SBP) is an effort to deploy coordinated beacon transmitters on 50&nbsp;MHz using a one-minute transmitting sequence of PI4, CW, and unmodulated carrier.  Since modern beacon transmitters are multi-mode and frequency-agile, beacons that normally transmit on other time-multiplexed modes such as WSPR can take part in the SBP when not transmitting in their primary mode.  Beacons alternating between frequencies on the same band should sign CALL/S when transmitting on the SBP frequency to ensure unique entries in band-specific propagation report databases.<ref name=\"SBP\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rudius.net/oz2m/sbp |title=OZ2M |date=20 April 2017 |first1=Bo (OZ2M) |last1=Hansen }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ionosonde]]\n* [[Electric beacon]]\n* [[OZ7IGY|OZ7IGY{{Snd}} the world's oldest beacon]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\">\n{{cite web\n|url         = https://www.iaru-r1.org/index.php/vhfuhsshf/1737-vhf-manager-handbook-version-8-00\n|title       = VHF Managers Handbook\n|version     = 7\n|publisher   = International Amateur Radio Union Region 1\n|format      = PDF\n|date        = January 2015\n|accessdate  = October 27, 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\">\n{{cite web\n |url=https://www.iaru-r2.org/documents/explorer/files/Plan%20de%20bandas%20%7C%20Band-plan/R2%20Band%20Plan%202016.pdf\n |title=IARU Region 2 Band Plan \n |publisher=International Amateur Radio Union Region 2 \n |date=October 14, 2016\n |accessdate=September 16, 2019\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.iaru-r3.org/newsite/wp-content/files/R3-004%20IARU%20Region%203%20Bandplan%20rev.2.pdf\n |title=IARU Region 3 Interim Band Plan\n |publisher=International Amateur Radio Union Region 3\n |date=September 3, 2019\n |accessdate=September 16, 2019\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=ARRLbandplan>\n{{cite web\n|url         = http://www.arrl.org/band-plan\n|title       = Band Plan\n|publisher   = [[American Radio Relay League]]\n|access-date = October 27, 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.ncdxf.org/pages/beacons.html IARU/NDXF International Beacon Project]\n* {{cite web | url=http://hamradio.pl/beacons/ | title=Amateur Radio Beacon List | publisher=Dawid SQ6EMM | accessdate=2012-12-06 | author=Dawid SQ6EMM | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322202543/http://hamradio.pl/beacons/ | archive-date=2012-03-22 | url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.70mhz.org/beacons.htm | title=The 70&nbsp;MHz Beacon List | publisher=The Four Metres Website | accessdate=2008-04-27 |author1=R.Wilkinson, G6GVI |author2=S.Cooper, GM4AFF |author3=B. Hansen, OZ2M | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080218132752/http://www.70mhz.org/beacons.htm | archive-date=2008-02-18 | url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web |author=Martin Harrison, G3USF | url=http://www.keele.ac.uk/depts/por/28.htm | title=Worldwide List of HF Beacons | accessdate=2008-04-27 | format=TEXT}}\n* {{cite web |author=Martin Harrison, G3USF | url=http://www.keele.ac.uk/depts/por/50.htm | title=Worldwide List of 50 Beacons | accessdate=2008-04-27 | format=TEXT}}\n<!--\n* {{cite web | url=http://users.iafrica.com/z/zs/zs5s/bulls/BEACON.TXT | format=TEXT | title=List of active HF Amateur Radio Beacons | author=Joost Schuitemaker, ZS5S | accessdate=2008-04-27}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://users.iafrica.com/z/zs/zs5s/bulls/BCNADD.TXT | format=TEXT | title=Additional HF Beacon Information | author=Joost Schuitemaker, ZS5S | accessdate=2008-04-27}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://users.iafrica.com/z/zs/zs5s/bulls/BCNQRT.TXT | format=TEXT | title=Inactive HF Beacons | author=Joost Schuitemaker, ZS5S | accessdate=2008-04-27}}\n-->\n*{{cite web|url=http://freenet-homepage.de/troesne/Beacons.html |title=The DL8AAM QSL Collection: QSLs from Radio Beacons |accessdate=2008-01-05 |author=Thomas M. R\u00f6sner, DL8AAM |year=2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070910195731/http://freenet-homepage.de/troesne/Beacons.html |archivedate=September 10, 2007 }} \n* {{cite journal | journal=CQ VHF | author=John Jaminet, W3HMS and Charlie Heisler, K3VDB | title=Building a beacon for 2401 MHz | volume=10 | issue=3 | publisher=CQ Communications, Inc | issn=1085-0708 | pages=44\u201346 | year=2007}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.g4jnt.com/5MHzBcnsWeb.pdf| title=Design and building of the 5&nbsp;MHz beacons, GB3RAL, GB3WES and GB3ORK | author=Andrew Talbot, G4JNT }}\n*{{cite web | url = http://www.g4jnt.com/BeaconPres-2.ppt | title=The Next Generation of Beacons for the 21st century | author=Andy Talbot, G4JNT | format = ppt }}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.microwavers.org/indexb.htm | publisher=UK Microwave Groups (UKMuG) | accessdate=2008-04-27 | title=UK Amateur Radio & Microwave Beacons }}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.rudius.net/oz2m/ngnb | title=The Next Generation Beacons platform | author=Bo Hansen, OZ2M}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.rudius.net/oz2m/ngnb/pi4.htm | title=PI4{{Snd}} a digital modulation for beacon purposes | author=Bo Hansen, OZ2M}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radio Propagation Beacon}}\n[[Category:Radio frequency propagation|Beacon]]\n[[Category:Beacons]]\n[[Category:Amateur radio]]\n", "text_old": "{{broader|Electric beacon}}\nAn '''amateur radio propagation beacon''' is a [[radio beacon]], whose purpose is the investigation of the [[radio propagation|propagation]] of radio signals. Most radio propagation beacons use [[amateur radio]] frequencies.  They can be found on [[Low frequency|LF]], [[Medium frequency|MF]], [[High frequency|HF]], [[Very high frequency|VHF]], [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]], and [[microwave]] frequencies.   Microwave beacons are also used as signal sources to test and calibrate antennas and receivers.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Andy Talbot, G4JNT| title=Amateur Beacons | journal=Radio User| issn=1748-8117 |date=May 2008 | volume=3 | issue=5 | pages=56\u201358 }} The article includes the following definition for beacons licensed in the Amateur Radio service: \"A station in the Amateur Service or Amateur Satellite Service that autonomously transmits in a fixed format, which may include repeated data or information, for the study of propagation, determination of frequency or bearing, or for other experimental purposes\".</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first1=Andy (G4JNT) |last1=Talbot |title=Amateur Beacons |journal=Radio User |issn=1748-8117 |date=August 2008 |volume=3 |issue=8 |pages=30\u201333 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Amateur Radio Union]] (IARU) and its member societies coordinate beacons established by radio amateurs.\n[[File:4U1UN beacon.ogg|thumb|right|Propagation beacon 4U1UN, transmitting from the [[headquarters of the United Nations]] in New York]]\n\n==Transmission characteristics==\nMost beacons operate in [[continuous wave]] (A1A) and transmit their identification ([[call sign]] and location). Some of them send long dashes to facilitate signal strength measurement. A small number of beacons transmit [[Morse code]] by [[frequency shift keying]] (F1A). A few beacons transmit signals in digital modulation modes, like [[radioteletype]] (F1B) and [[PSK31]] (G1B).\n\n==Legality==\nIn the US, unattended beacons on frequencies lower than the 10-meter band are not legal.<ref name=\"Keeton\">{{cite web |url=https://groups.io/g/QRPLabs/message/12013 |title=Re: Beacon Operating frequencies |first1=Kelly R. (K7MHI) |last1=Keeton |date=17 November 2016 |accessdate=28 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==2200-meter beacons==\nAmateur experiments in the [[2200-meter band]] (135.7\u2013137.8&nbsp;kHz) often involve operating temporary beacons.\n\n==1750-meter beacons==\nIn the United States and Canada, unlicensed experimenters (\"[[LowFER]]s\") establish low power beacons on radio frequencies between 160&nbsp;kHz and 190&nbsp;kHz.\n\n==160-meter beacons==\nThe International Amateur Radio Union [[International Telecommunication Union region|Region 2]] ([[North America|North]] and [[South America]]) bandplan for the [[160-meter band]] reserves the range 1999&nbsp;[[kilohertz|kHz]] to 2000&nbsp;kHz for propagation beacons.\n\n==10-meter beacons==\nMost [[high frequency]] radio propagation beacons are found in the [[10-meter band]] (28&nbsp;MHz), where they are good indicators of [[Sporadic E]] ionospheric propagation.  According to IARU bandplans, the following 28&nbsp;MHz frequencies are allocated to radio propagation beacons:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! IARU Region\n! Beacon Sub-bands (MHz)\n|-\n| R1\n|\n* 28.190\u201328.199 Regional time-shared\n* 28.199\u201328.201 The International Beacon Project\n* 28.201\u201328.225 Continuous duty\n|-\n| R2<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/>\n|\n* 28.190\u201328.199 Regional time-shared\n* 28.199\u201328.201 The International Beacon Project\n* 28.201\u201328.225 Beacons, continuous duty\n* 28.225\u201328.300 Shared\n|-\n| R3\n|\n* 28.190\u201328.200 The International Beacon Project\n|}\n\n==6-meter beacons==\nDue to unpredictable and intermittent long distance propagation, usually achieved by a combination of ionospheric conditions, beacons are very important in providing early warning for [[6-meter band]] (50&nbsp;MHz) openings. Beacons operate in the lower part of the band, traditionally in the range 50.000&nbsp;MHz to 50.080&nbsp;MHz.\n\nThe IARU is encouraging individual beacons to move to 50.4&nbsp;MHz to 50.5&nbsp;MHz to assist with the establishment of the [[#Synchronized Beacon Project|Synchronized Beacon Project]].<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>  In the [[United States]], the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) only permits unattended 6-meter beacon stations to operate between 50.060&nbsp; and 50.080&nbsp;MHz.<ref name=\"T47CFR97.203d\">{{CodeFedReg|47|97|203|(d)}}</ref>\n\n==4-meter beacons==\nSeveral countries in [[International Telecommunication Union region|ITU Region 1]] have access to frequencies in the 70&nbsp;MHz region, called the [[4-meter band]].  The band shares many propagation characteristics with 6 meters.  The preferred location for beacons is 70.000\u201370.090&nbsp;MHz;<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/> however, in countries where this segment is not allocated to Amateur Radio, beacons may operate elsewhere in the band.\n\n==VHF/UHF beacons==\nBeacons on 144&nbsp;MHz and higher frequencies are mainly used to identify [[Radio propagation#Tropospheric modes|tropospheric radio propagation]] openings. It is not uncommon for VHF and UHF beacons to use directional antennas.  Frequencies set aside for beacons on VHF and UHF bands vary widely in different ITU regions and countries.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Band\n! colspan=\"3\" | Beacon Sub-band (MHz)\n|-\n! ITU Region 1\n! ITU Region 2\n! ITU Region 3\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2 meters|2&nbsp;m]]\n| align=\"center\" | 144.400\u2013144.491<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 144.275\u2013144.300<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | none<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[1.25 meters|1.25&nbsp;m]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| align=\"center\" | 222.050\u2013222.060<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[70 centimeters|70&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 432.400\u2013432.490<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 432.300\u2013432.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | none<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[33 centimeters|33&nbsp;cm]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| align=\"center\" | 903.000\u2013903.100<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[23 centimeters|23&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 1,296.800\u20131,296.994<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 1,296.200\u20131,296.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | none<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[13 centimeters|13&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 2,320.800\u20132,321.000<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 2,304.300\u20132,304.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 2,304.300\u20132,304.400<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\nThe beacon sub-bands in the [[United Kingdom]] also reflect IARU Region 1 recommendations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qsl.net/g3yrc/Bandplans/UK%20VHF.htm |title=Amateur Radio UK VHF Bandplan |accessdate=2008-04-27 |website=Great Yarmouth Radio Club |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531002059/http://www.qsl.net/g3yrc/Bandplans/UK%20VHF.htm |archive-date=2008-05-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==SHF/microwave beacons==\nIn addition to identifying propagation, microwave beacons are also used as signal sources to test and calibrate antennas and receivers.  [[Super high frequency|SHF]] beacons are not as common as beacons on the lower bands, and beacons above the [[3-centimeter band]] (10&nbsp;GHz) are unusual.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Band\n! colspan=\"3\" | Beacon Sub-band (MHz)\n|-\n! ITU Region 1\n! ITU Region 2\n! ITU Region 3\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[9 centimeters|9&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 3,400.800\u20133,400.995<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 3,456.300\u20133,457.000<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 3,456.300\u20133,457.000<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[5 centimeters|5&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5,760.800\u20135,760.990<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 5,760.300\u20135,761.000<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 5,760.300\u20135,761.000<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[3 centimeters|3&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 10,368.800\u201310,368.990<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 10,368.300\u201310,368.400<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/><ref name=ARRLbandplan/>\n| align=\"center\" | 10.368.300\u201310.368.400<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[1.2 centimeters|1.2&nbsp;cm]]\n| align=\"center\" | 24,048.800\u201324,048.995<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 24,048.750\u201324,048.995<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 24,048.750\u201324,048.995<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\"/>\n|}\n\n==Beacon projects==\nMost radio propagation beacons are operated by individual radio amateurs or amateur radio societies and clubs. As a result, there are frequent additions and deletions to the lists of beacons. There are, however a few major projects coordinated by organizations like the [[International Amateur Radio Union]] (IARU).\n\n===IARU Beacon Project===\n{{main|International Beacon Project}}\n[[File:NCDXF beacons.ogg|thumb|right|Beacons from Finland and Madeira on 14.100&nbsp;MHz]]\nThe International Beacon Project (IBP), which is coordinated by the [http://www.ncdxf.org/pages/beacons.html Northern California DX Foundation] and the [[International Amateur Radio Union]], consists of 18&nbsp;[[high frequency]] propagation beacons worldwide, which transmit in turns on 14.100&nbsp;MHz, 18.110&nbsp;MHz, 21.150&nbsp;MHz, 24.930&nbsp;MHz, and 28.200&nbsp;MHz.<ref name=\"ncdxf\">{{cite web\n |publisher=Northern California DX Foundation \n |year=2008 \n |url=http://www.ncdxf.org/beacons.html \n |title=International Beacon Project \n |accessdate=2008-02-27 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227235431/http://www.ncdxf.org/beacons.html \n |archivedate=2007-12-27 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n===DARC Beacon Project===\nThe [[Deutscher Amateur-Radio-Club]] sponsors two beacons which transmit from [[Scheggerott]], near [[Kiel]] ({{Coor Maidenhead|54.6875|9.79167|yes}}).<ref>{{cite web |title=Aurora beacon DK\u00d8WCY |url=http://www.dk0wcy.de |website=[[Deutscher Amateur-Radio-Club]] e.V. (DARC) |accessdate=2008-05-03 |year=2004 }}</ref> These beacons are DRA5 on 5195&nbsp;kHz and DK0WCY on 10144&nbsp;kHz. In addition to identification and location, every 10 minutes, these beacons transmit solar and [[geomagnetic]] bulletins. Transmissions are in Morse code for aural reception, RTTY and PSK31.<ref>{{cite book | title=Technical Topics Scrapbook{{Snd}} All 50 years | chapter=The DK0WCY/DRA5 Propagation Beacons | pages=98 | author=Pat Hawker, G3VA | publisher=[[Radio Society of Great Britain]] | year=2008 | isbn=978-1-905086-39-9 | location=Potters Bar, UK }}</ref> DK0WCY operates also a limited service beacon on 3579&nbsp;kHz at 0720\u20130900 and 1600\u20131900 local time.\n\n===RSGB 5 MHz Beacon Project===\nThe [[Radio Society of Great Britain]] operates a radio propagation beacon GB3ORK on 5290&nbsp;kHz, transmitting every 15 minutes commencing at 2 minutes past the hour.  It is located in the [[Orkney Islands]] ({{Coor Maidenhead|59.0208|-3.20833|yes}}).\n\n===The GB3RAL VHF Beacon Cluster===\nGB3RAL, which is located at the [[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]], transmits continuously on a number of low-band and mid-band VHF frequencies{{Snd}} 40050, 50050, 60050 and 70050&nbsp;kHz{{Snd}} as well as 28215&nbsp;kHz in the 10-meter amateur band.<ref>{{cite journal\n| journal=RadCom\n| publisher=[[Radio Society of Great Britain]]\n| pages=65\u201369\n| title=The GB3RAL VHF Beacon cluster\n| author=Mike Willis, G0MJW\n| volume=84\n| issue=4\n| issn=1367-1499\n| date=April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Weak Signal Propagation Reporter Network (WSPR)===\nA large-scale beacon project is underway using the WSPR transmission scheme included with the [[WSJT (Amateur radio software)|WSJT]] software suite.  The loosely coordinated beacon transmitters and receivers, collectively known as the WSPRnet, report the real-time propagation characteristics of a number of frequency bands and geographical locations via  \nthe Internet.  The WSPRnet website provides detailed propagation report databases and real-time graphical maps of propagation paths.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcome to the Weak Signal Propagation Reporter Network |url=http://wsprnet.org |website=[[WSPR (amateur radio software)|WSPRNet]] }}</ref>\n\n===Synchronized Beacon Project===\nThe Synchronized Beacon Project (SBP) is an effort to deploy coordinated beacon transmitters on 50&nbsp;MHz using a one-minute transmitting sequence of PI4, CW, and unmodulated carrier.  Since modern beacon transmitters are multi-mode and frequency-agile, beacons that normally transmit on other time-multiplexed modes such as WSPR can take part in the SBP when not transmitting in their primary mode.  Beacons alternating between frequencies on the same band should sign CALL/S when transmitting on the SBP frequency to ensure unique entries in band-specific propagation report databases.<ref name=\"SBP\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rudius.net/oz2m/sbp |title=OZ2M |date=20 April 2017 |first1=Bo (OZ2M) |last1=Hansen }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ionosonde]]\n* [[Electric beacon]]\n* [[OZ7IGY|OZ7IGY{{Snd}} the world's oldest beacon]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IARU-R1-bandplan\">\n{{cite web\n|url         = https://www.iaru-r1.org/index.php/vhfuhsshf/1737-vhf-manager-handbook-version-8-00\n|title       = VHF Managers Handbook\n|version     = 7\n|publisher   = International Amateur Radio Union Region 1\n|format      = PDF\n|date        = January 2015\n|accessdate  = October 27, 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IARU-R2-bandplan\">\n{{cite web\n |url=https://www.iaru-r2.org/documents/explorer/files/Plan%20de%20bandas%20%7C%20Band-plan/R2%20Band%20Plan%202016.pdf\n |title=IARU Region 2 Band Plan \n |publisher=International Amateur Radio Union Region 2 \n |date=October 14, 2016\n |accessdate=September 16, 2019\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IARU-R3-bandplan\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.iaru-r3.org/newsite/wp-content/files/R3-004%20IARU%20Region%203%20Bandplan%20rev.2.pdf\n |title=IARU Region 3 Interim Band Plan\n |publisher=International Amateur Radio Union Region 3\n |date=September 3, 2019\n |accessdate=September 16, 2019\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=ARRLbandplan>\n{{cite web\n|url         = http://www.arrl.org/band-plan\n|title       = Band Plan\n|publisher   = [[American Radio Relay League]]\n|access-date = October 27, 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.ncdxf.org/pages/beacons.html IARU/NDXF International Beacon Project]\n* {{cite web | url=http://hamradio.pl/beacons/ | title=Amateur Radio Beacon List | publisher=Dawid SQ6EMM | accessdate=2012-12-06 | author=Dawid SQ6EMM | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322202543/http://hamradio.pl/beacons/ | archive-date=2012-03-22 | url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web | url=http://www.70mhz.org/beacons.htm | title=The 70&nbsp;MHz Beacon List | publisher=The Four Metres Web